## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2019 University of Rochester Medical Center settlement** — URMC paid $3 million to HHS OCR following an investigation triggered by two separate incidents involving lost and stolen unencrypted portable devices.

What made the URMC case directly relevant to today's topic is OCR's finding: URMC had conducted risk analyses but had not implemented encryption as a result of those analyses, and had not documented a sufficient reason why encryption was not reasonable and appropriate. The addressable specification issue was central to the case. OCR's position was not that addressable specifications are optional — it was that organizations must either implement them or document a legitimate justification for an alternative approach. URMC had neither implemented encryption nor documented a credible alternative.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the URMC settlement is a concrete illustration of why the "addressable" label for encryption requirements does not mean those requirements are optional in practice. The MyClinic High confidentiality categorization, combined with the direct patient safety and privacy implications of ePHI exposure, means that the addressable encryption specifications are effectively required — and that is what the requirements matrix documents explicitly.

The $3 million settlement also illustrates why compliance documentation is not bureaucratic overhead. It is the evidence that demonstrates reasonable and appropriate safeguards were implemented — the defense against regulatory liability in the event of an incident.

