## What I Am Still Thinking About

One complexity I want to think through more carefully: the international dimension of OpenMRS deployments. OpenMRS was originally designed for healthcare in low- and middle-income countries — many of its real-world deployments are in sub-Saharan Africa, South and Southeast Asia, and Latin America. For those deployments, HIPAA does not apply. Instead, the applicable framework might be GDPR if the deployment involves EU residents, local data protection laws, or no formal framework at all if the jurisdiction lacks health data protection legislation.

The security requirements analysis I completed today is specific to the US HIPAA-covered context of MyClinic. But the principles — access control, audit logging, encryption, risk assessment, breach notification — are consistent across frameworks even where the specific regulatory citation differs. A clinic in Kenya deploying OpenMRS faces the same underlying security risks documented in Days 37 and 38; the regulatory driver for implementing the controls is different, but the controls themselves are the same.

I want to develop a brief international compliance addendum for this project that addresses what the requirements picture looks like for a non-US OpenMRS deployment — because that context is actually more common for OpenMRS globally than the US healthcare context I have been focused on.

